<TITLE> Zoellick must restore confidence in W Bank: France </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 POTSDAM, Germany, May 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Robert Zoellick, slated to replace Paul Wolfowitz as president of the World Bank, must move swiftly to restore confidence in the poverty-fighting institution, France's foreign minister said on Wednesday. "Between the partners and the World Bank it is mainly a question of confidence," Bernard Kouchner told reporters ahead of a meeting of G8 foreign ministers in this east German city. "I hope Mr Zoellick will re-establish, or establish, our confidence in the World Bank. It is absolutely crucial." Asked if Zoellick was the right man to replace Wolfowitz, who was forced to resign over his authorisation of a pay rise for his bank-employee companion, Kouchner replied: "Certainly". US President George W Bush is expected to formally announce his choice of Zoellick, a former US trade representative, later on Wednesday. The controversy over Wolfowitz and his weeks-long battle to hold on to his job has deepened rifts among bank staff already disgruntled by his anti-corruption agenda and prompted sharp criticism from shareholder countries. The United States has traditionally named the World Bank president, but some bank member countries and some US lawmakers have urged the administration to throw the process open to a global pool of candidates after the Wolfowitz row
